observations.recommendation:
Issue Certificates of Completion for the completed projects to be used as basis by the Municipal Accountant in the reclassification of these items to their proper PPE or expense accounts;

Take up the corresponding depreciation expenses of these projects from the time these were completed; and



Reconcile the amounts recorded in the ledger with the amounts incurred to date recorded by the Engineering Office so as to present fairly the financial statements of the Municipality as at a given period.

Municipal Engineer, Municipal Accountant and other concerned municipal officials and employees agreed to reconcile their respective records, conduct regular monitoring to ensure that fund transfers are implemented and liquidated within the prescribed period;

Municipal Mayor and other concerned officials agreed to return or seek authority from the source agencies to realign the excess/unspent balances of the fully implemented projects. Likewise, assess the feasibility/necessity of the projects that remain unimplemented, otherwise return the funds to the source agency; and 

Municipal Accountant agreed to analyze the accounts with negative balances and identify the causes thereon and effect the necessary adjustments to reflect the correct balances.

We recommended and Management agreed to instruct:
the Municipal Accountant to coordinate with the Engineering Office to trace and reconcile the status of the projects under CIP and make necessary adjusting entries to reflect the correct balance in the PPE accounts and recognize the depreciation expenses thereon, if necessary;
the Municipal Engineer to issue the SWA for every payment of labor cost of the projects and Certificate of Completion as basis of the Accounting Office for the timely reclassification of the accounts under CIP and to its proper PPE account and facilitate monitoring thereof;
develop a system of Project Identification (ID) Number which will be included in the particulars/project name in the Program of Works, Purchase Request, Purchase Order, Inspection and Acceptance, and Disbursement Voucher to facilitate consistency in the recording of the cost incurred for a particular project in the subsidiary ledger, given the numerous projects implemented by administration; and
Municipal Engineer to regularly monitor the implementation of the projects so that the up-to-date status is recorded in their monitoring report.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor instruct the Municipal Agriculture Officer, who agreed to:
coordinate with the Provincial Government on the Sugbusog Program pertaining to the raising of native pigs and chickens so that appropriate action can be taken such as reimbursements for the procurement of the native pigs, and the subsequent recording in the books of accounts;
submit inventory of native chickens to be used as basis of the Municipal Accountant in recording using the fair value at the time it was acquired and the subsequent gains/loss for the changes thereof;
coordinate regularly with the Municipal Accountant for any receipts and disposal of the biological assets so facilitate the timely and proper recording in the books of accounts; and
submit the lacking documentary requirements to facilitate the evaluation of the Request for Relief of Accountability for the cattle and native pig.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor through the concerned officials ensure:
that the expenditures related to the current year’s response to urgent needs during emergency situations be charged to the 30 per cent QRF of the current year instead of the previous years;
that the identified PPAs to be funded out of the unexpended balance of previous years’ LDRRMF shall be incorporated in the LDRRMFIP to effectively plan and manage the fund.
